1.4 Unified Criterion for Abundance: Three Probabilities

The cosmic abundance of any nuclide is determined by three probabilities:

Synthesis Probability: The probability that the nuclide is produced via various pathways. If a channel is blocked by Path 3, its contribution is zero, but the nuclide may still be synthesized via other channels.
Continued Fusion Probability: The probability that the nuclide, as a reactant, continues to fuse into heavier nuclides.
Fission Probability: The probability of the nuclide undergoing internal stress tearing and fissioning back into lighter nuclides.
These three factors together determine the net retention of the nuclide on the mass spectrum:

Net Retention ∝ Synthesis Probability × (1 − Continued Fusion Probability − Fission Probability)

Abundance peaks occur at nuclides where "synthesis probability is relatively considerable, and both continued fusion probability and fission probability are low." Abundance valleys occur conversely.

